title: Lens cap for SJ4000 camera (GoPro lookalike)

description.text:
I designed this because other lens caps I had used tended to fall off leaving the lens exposed. This one will clip on securely and will not come off unless you want it to. It is designed for the SJ4000, which is a low cost copy of the GoPro.
It will probably also fit a GoPro but I don't know for sure because I don't have one to try it on.

Important: the Sketchup object is 10 times real size. If you use it to export an STL rather than using the one I provided make sure you scale down the STL after exporting it.
(I always use this 10 times scaling to mitigate some bugs in Sketchup, and then scale down the STL afterwards) Print in 0.25mm layers with a 0.4mm nozzle and slice with edge width of 0.4mm. The edge width setting is important to leave some space between the perimeters to get enough flexibility. I printed it in HIPS, which I find better than PLA and ABS in all regards. It is stronger, gives better finish and warps much less than ABS.

While atttending the makerbot demonstration/workshop in Philadelphia a couple of weeks ago, is saw the OWL WRAP EarPhone Caddy and was delighted by it. I asked Zach to print one for me and have been using it and showing it to anyone interested. I was wondering how to get the word out about the Makerbot machine and I thought that having a functional Thingy made by the machine; to hand out as a MakerBot business card would be nice, so I present the MakerBot Earphone Caddy; mach 1, mod 0, for immediate development. Some of the things I built into this model are: (hopefully) 1) machine friendliness, using the machine's attributes in the development of the part. If you print it standing up from the flat at the bottom I am guessing that the machine will handle the gradual overhangs ok. and 2) The advertising text (Makerbot your idea) is made very shallow in the hopes that it will take advantage of the way the machine layers the plastic and be readable: kind of like raised lettering and. 3) You can print a dozen of them at a time if you stand them up like dominoes. Some issues to be fine tuned prior to putting this thingy into production are: 1) The the head phones need to easily pop in and out of their holes during retrieval and wrap up and stay put while in storage. I find that the way I wrap the wire helps to keep my OWL WRAP's phones in place while in my pocket but it would be nice to have that worked out more clearly in future iterations. 2) The rectangular hole for the jack should be ambidextrous so the jack can slip under the wrapped wires into the hole's depression in a 'tight fit' sort of way, but not through it. 3) The text could be adjusted to be as clear as possible (I need to see a printed sample print to think thru that one), and 4) The vertical build of the part should be supportive of the machine's building technique, but again the sample will speak to that. I am using SolidWorks to produce the model and I am interested in helping to develop it into a cool little way to get the word out about this amazing price breakthrough into the world of rapid prototyping. The fact that you can print you idea(s) on a machine that costs less than $1,000.00 is going to bring RP technology into ubiquity. If anyone can print this with a MakerBot and send me a copy I'll be happy inspect it, use it, refine it, and try again until we get it right. P.S. this idea may work well with other RP machines, but my intention is to refine it for MakerBot because The MakerBot is the first machine to get below the $1,000.00 price mark. I think the personality of the builds of this machine are beautiful and I don\'t intend for this prototype to become some slick marketing tool. Having the finished part be a real prototype built on the machine that it represents is just too zen to forego. Chas.

description.text:
Desk organizer system for those people who have lots of pens, pencils, paper clips, post-its, and more. Minimalist design, using as little plastic as possible.
The square has 10, 20, 40, and 80mm heights. The post-it version has a finger pull. The rectangle has 10 and 80 mm heights; reason being you can actually put a 10mm rectangle under an 80mm rectangle, and it becomes a relatively clever stash spot (or savings account because it holds US bills perfectly).

I printed with PLA. The wall is 1mm thick, building each layer on two passes (with a .5mm extrusion). The taller pieces have some small reinforcements built in to counteract the shrinkage factor. The bottom layer is .6 mm thick, or three layers with .2mm heights.
Overall, this system does not consume that much plastic, because they get all the strength they need from snapping together.

A space ship designed for deep universe exploration.  Named after Marco Polo the explorer.  It has the copper or bronze look because of all the space debris that has made contact with the hull.  
It is designed to fit the stand that comes with it.

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Notes: I suggest printing out the top of the ship at highest resolution to retain the details and the bottom at medium resolution. The wings should be printed out in highest resolution. The stand can be printed at medium resolution. The wings and hull bottom should be printed out with support for the wing connectors but with no rafts. The top and the stand requires no supports or rafts. If you have trouble getting the top and bottom to print without flipping up on the ends, you may want to try rafts.

The copper affect was created by spay painting the model with shiny copper color (see photos of spray paint)  and letting it set - then spraying with the metal silver and quickly taking a non-shedding rag to the outer edges to give it that worn look,
Design and modelled in Modo.

Updated the scale of the model - Jan 2016
The default size should fit a Makerbot Replicator 2 build volume. If you need to resize, resize the parts consistently. Start with the Ship Top and make that the maximum size of your build plate and then make a note of what percentage it was sized. Then use that same percentage on the other parts. I also included one set of wings with propulsion extensions and another without. You only need to print one or the other not both - your choice. You can flip the wings with the propulsion on top or on the bottom of the wings - your choice. Print out the various components and you should glue them together. The wings slide in the wing connectors on the bottom part. I used Lepage's Liquid Steel/metal epoxy and used hobby clamps to hold the bottom and top together. I added a bit of glue to the wing connectors so those would be permanent. I didn't glue the model on the stand, it just slides on or off. When I tried this with the Makebot software, it didn't create proper supports for the wing connectors. If it doesn't printer properly you may have to hold the wings on while the glue sets. I used Simplify3D and manually created supports on the bottom section just for the wing connectors (the rest doesn't need support). In regards to printing out the stand - again Simplify3D comes in handy here because I reduced the speed to 40% once in got to the thin part of the stand. I also used a house fan at that point in the print so it didn't get too hot. My first couple of prints with the Replicator 2 were very rough on the backside of the stand because it was so thin and the plastic gets too hot and doesn't get a chance to cool before the next layer. I have noticed my Rep 2 does not do well with thin structures that protrude above the main print unless I do both strategies (slow down the speed and use an additional fan).

A small plastic block for mounting print boards and the like. A zip tie is pushed through the block from one side, leaving the "head" in the large part of the hole.
A bolt or screw is pushed through from the other side, and used to fasten the block. The tail of the zip tie is sticking out. title: WiFi dongle cover for the Compro TN600RW and TR900RW Wireless cameras

description.text: I recently got one of these awesome Compro TN600RW cameras (http://www.comprousa.com/en/surveillance/product/tn600r/index.html) and the first thing that stood out like a sore thumb was the WiFi dongle's blinding blue LED. I got this camera to use in my child's room and at night this LED would light up her whole room and flash with activity. Needless to say that's not going to help her sleep. So I designed this cover to fit over the WiFi dongle and block out most of the light while still allowing airflow for cooling. I've been using it for a couple weeks now and it made a HUGE difference. I printed the one in the pictures with Gizmodorks black PLA. Infill doesn't really matter as the walls are only thick enough for solid lines so it's pretty much 100% infill. Obviously this will only work if the camera's base is facing down (not using the ceiling mount). You could probably use a small rubber band to secure it if your camera is mounted to the ceiling. Judging by the pictures this will also fit the Compro TN900RW as it appears to use the same dongle setup.
Print the cover, place it over the WiFi dongle and you're done.

Replacement gasket for a kitchen sink strainer. This is obviously made to be printed with a soft plastic, in this case NinjaFlex.  
This is a great alternative to buying a new strainer, and it works extremely well. I am extremely impressed by the NinjaFlex material.  
This is also a very simple example of OpenScad. It can be customized to different shapes of gaskets. Notice that gaskets usually indicate their size. In this case, it was 51.6mm/34.5mm outside/inside diameter, and height of 6mm.

Print in NinjaFlex.
For best results, I printed at 30mm/sec, with a layer height of 0.2mm. The filling percentage will affect the rigidity of the part. I strongly suggest to stay at 30% fill factor or lower, other the part will be very stiff and hard to install. I found that rectilinear filling ("straight lines") is easier to print than hexagonal patterns.

It is difficult to design a good landing gear (and foldable) that gets mounted on the bottom plate (I am still thinking on how to do that).
In the mean time I looked online for landing gear for my F550, and found a few that get mounted on the arms, but not foldable! again.. difficult for transporting my F550. So I spent some time, and designed this foldable landing gear.
One of the issues when I designed it, was how to make it stay folded or unfolded; the solution is simple... "R Clips"
I designed it with 2 mm holes, for the R clip to insert when folded, or unfolded.
I went to my local hardware store, and I could not find R Clips that matched perfectly, so I made my own from a wire coat hanger :) LOL The hole in the middle is 4 mm diameter. I used M4 screw 16 mm length; there is no need for the nut because it goes in by force, and it "creates" the thread in the top 3D printed piece. Usually 3D printers make holes smaller than design. But if you want piece of mind, I suggest to use a little longer screw (20 mm length), and use an M4 lock nut.

Add the specifics for your spool. Print 2, insert into spool, place back on rod. The parameters are as follows:
Spool Size is the ID of the spool.
Tab Thickness is how thick the tabs that go into the spool will be.
Backplate Rim is the size of the rim.

Spool Rod Size is the size of the spool rod through the center.

remixed_from.title: V2 Fishing rod REEL - MOULINET Version2

description.text:
This is a fly fishing reel that I recently designed.  The main goal was to make something usable that has as few moving parts as possible for simplicity of assembly and printing.  Also, because I generally dislike the clicking sound associated with many fly reels I decided to take a different approach to generating resistance on the line.  By arranging magnets attracted to each other on either half of the reel as you pull out line there is resistance as you force each pair away from one another.  
Remixes are encouraged!  This is a work in progress so any contributions or constructive criticism are welcome.  I have included a copy of the sketchup file that I used to make this for your convenience.  After seeing krapouere's fishing reel I was inspired myself to make this one.  Although, I haven't actually tried it out on the river yet but hopefully will soon.  
Happy Fishing!

First print off all the parts, depending on your printer some tolerances may be tight so sand down any parts and needed. You will also need some disk magnets, and a 608 skate bearing. 1.) Secure "attachment" part to "magnet_half" with a couple flat head machine screws.
2.) Secure "handle_small" to "handle_half" with a nut/bolt or machine screw
3.) Place washer and 608 bearing onto M8 bold and slide the parts through "handle_half" center then "magnet_half" and secure into place.
4.) Arrange magnets such that they will be attracted together when one of each pair is across from one another on "handle_half" and "magnet_half" respectively.
// I assembled mine with the all poles facing the same direction for a given half. In this way there will be 3 major points of attraction, 6 magnets total, for each revolution of the handle.//
5.) Place a generous portion of hot glue or another adhesive in each magnet holder and put in magnets.
// I picked up some Disc Neodymium Magnets Dia 1/2X1/8" for use in this project //
6.) Allow adhesive to dry.
7.) Add some line, attach to rod, add a fly, and catch some fish.
//The actual hard part!//

description.text:
Torch diffuser to spread the light from a Ryobi one+ xenon spotlight, to light up a wider area.  
I bought one of these torches to use on site for lighting the inside of transfer chutes while taking videos. Since the light was so focused, it needed something to spread the light. I got sick of having baking paper taped over the lens of the torch, so I designed this clip to mount either a circle of baking paper or thin clouded perspex.  
Requries two short (or one long) cable tie, to secure it in place (it will stay in place without, but is more secure with the cable ties). Cable ties must be no wider than 5mm.  
Along with the STL files, I included the Solidworks file for the torch body, incase anyone wants to have a play with similar stuffplay things.

• Cut a circle of thin clouded perspex (<=2mm thick), diameter 114mm
  • Print the Torch Clip.
  • Secure the perspex using the torch clip, then secure in place using cable ties, as shown in the photos
    • OR
  • Cut a circle of baking paper, diameter 114mm
  • Print the Torch Clip.
  • Print the Paper Ring.
  • Fit the paper to the Torch Clip using the Paper Ring (the spikes on the Paper Ring will line up with the indentations in the Torch Clip)
  • Mount the torch clip, then secure in place using cable ties, as shown in the photos
    • HAVE FUN WITH IT! Try using the Paper Ring to mount some clear plastic (e.g. glad wrap/cling film), then draw the Bat Signal on it!

title: Solidoodle Jigsaw Extruder Replacement w/ Fan Shroud and Receiver - MK5 Compatible for Hexagon and Other Hotends.

description.text:
This is meant to replace and accompany another thing:
lawsy's Mk5 parts (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:111213) I have two replacement bases for the above parts, in addition to fan mounts and a receiver. My bases are designed to help extruding softer filament. Sometimes softer or more flexible filament can bend a little bit instead of trying to extrude. My bases try to alleviate extrusion issues for those types of filament by constricting the distance from the stepper to the hotend opening. . Base3 is more aggressive than Base2 as far as guiding the filament is concerned. Base2 should be the default option unless you are having issues with your filament. The bases are meant for groove mount hotends and give enough heatsink room to support the size of the hexagon hotend, That was the intention with them, however they should also work for many other hotends. You will probably want to loosen the hobbed pulley/gear attached to the extruder stepper motor when mounting to ensure it aligns correctly with the directed filament guide.. The directed fan mount and receiver are sized for the hexagon hotend, but they may work with others. The directed fan mount should work with most hotends, and will definitely work with any j-head style. The receiver, however, has a piece that extends past the filament guide and would run into either the heat block or heatsink of any non-hexagon hotend. If you want to try the receiver without a hexagon anyway, you could probably just snap off that part of the piece if your hotend ends up running into it. There is support material included for all pieces. If you need to use a knife to remove the support material, you might want to revisit your printing settings. The bases have support for the tension arm mount, as well as support for the spacing of the stepper motor. The directed fan mount has support for its accessory clips. You should be able to apply force against the print direction, then slide them out. The directed fan mount receiver has two tiny supports for the mounting hole bulges. As far as testing goes, only base 3 is untested as of this writing. Base 2 has served me well enough for everything other than ninjaflex, so I haven't had a need to switch just yet. The pictures are of the complete assembly using Base2 - Base2, Receiver, Fan Mount. There is an action picture of the assembly whilst in the process of printing a PET+ calibration cube. I plan on replacing all extruder parts with PET+ due to the strength, temperature, and print quality characteristics. This thing is close to being finalized. All pieces (outside potentially base3) are very much in fully working order. Please excuse how dirty my hexagon is in the pictures. I have very much been abusing it. I went through 3 J-Head MK V-BVs before going all-metal. I feel dumb now. All metal hotends are the way to go. Lining ends up limiting temperatures and is really just a cost-saving manufacturing means in most cases. All metal is the way to go. I have a spare cartridge and thermistor for the hexagon. I don't think I will need them any time soon. One major issue with the J-Heads I had purchased was that the cartridge was "glued" in with cement. Additionally, the thermistor leads were very weak. Hexagon kits come with really solid and reliable parts that exhibit neither of those weaknesses. I'm not trying to sell the Hexagon, but to me it's obvious why it's popular, versatile, cheap to produce, and above all, very usable for a variety of filaments.

I based these models off of lawsy's jigsaw replacement (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:111213). I have provided a replacement base piece, and optional pieces to accompany it. The base pieces have support material. There is support material under the filament receptacle, as well as the tension arm mount. The material should snap off with little effort. The directed fan shround has support material for the mounting clips. If you apply a little force in the opposite direction of the print, it should become loose and then easily slide out. When mounted, it should not jiggle. It should have a very firm mount. The fan receiver has support material under its mounting nubs. The nubs are attached to a piece that has room to bend. I ended up breaking off one of the mounting nubs as the tight fit was enough to hold it in place with just 1 nub. If the (U) shaped piece runs into your hotend, I recommend breaking the piece off. It should snap off easily. The sizing of it was designed for the hexagon hotend.

title: Remake of Support and Fan duct for Solidoodle 4 (with new extruder)

description.text:
Thanks Miroule for creating the original to perfectly fit the Solidoodle 4 with the latest stock hot end. It was hard to find a mount for the SD4 that was this simple to attach/de-attach. I made two small modifications that fix the melting issue and improve the airflow:

  • Made the support about 5-6mm wider to prevent the fan mount from touching the hot end heater block and melting. This requires 2x M3 x 30mm long screws + 2 nuts to attach the mount to the support.

  • The original support was slightly touching the extruder pulley in my SD4. A notch was added to prevent this.

  • Modified the fan mount to be able to fit a 40mm x 40mm x 20mm 12V fan, instead of the original mount which only fits a 40x40x10 fan. The airflow doubles with the bigger fan and this makes a significant difference.
    • This is still in progress because an improvement to the fan mount is needed to really increase the airflow.

Same instructions as the original design with some additions:

  • Must print in ABS at 50% or above to reduce chances of melting the part

  • Need longer screws: 2x M3 x 30mm and two M3 nuts.

  • Need to dremel or file the holes in the fan mount to fit the nuts.

  • In case you don't have a 40x40x20 fan handy, I have also included a separate STL file for the original mount ( fits 40x40x10 fan) so it's all in one place.

title: Future Biometrics by Jillian Weise, a 3D Printed Broadside

description.text:
Future Biometrics is a poem by Jillian Weise first published in the March 2015 issue of Poetry ( http://www.poetryfoundation.org/poetrymagazine/poem/250084 ) and presented here as a 3D printed broadside. It has been translated into braille by Sean Tikkun ( http://www.thingiverse.com/jaqtikkun/about ) and transformed into modular forms by Tom Burtonwood. Poetry Foundation blog post: http://www.poetryfoundation.org/harriet/2015/04/come-say-hello-at-awp-see-the-first-3d-printed-broadside/ http://www.jillianweise.com/
http://seantikkun.net/ The inspiration for this project came out of a conversation I had with Fred Sasaki from the Poetry Foundation last summer. Fred visited my studio at the Art Institute of Chicago when I was Artist in Residence there in 2014. I had just published “Folium,” my second 3D printed book, which includes braille page numbers and corresponding braille descriptions for the 3D scanned bas relief works published in it from the AIC collection. Fred and I started talking about the possibilities of a 3D printed broadside using braille. “Folium,” like “Future Biometrics,” is shared via the website Thingiverse. With “Folium” I used an OpenSCAD braille generator designed by Sean Tikkun to create the braille elements. OpenSCAD is an open source solid modeling tool used by many people in the 3D printing community. Sean and I had been looking to collaborate on further projects and so this project with the Poetry Foundation seemed like a good fit for us. Sean translated Jillian Weise’s poem “Future Biometrics” into braille and sent me the files saved as STLs. I designed the modules using Rhino 3D a computer modeling program used by industrial designers, architects and artists alike. At first I wrapped the braille dots around a form modeled to resemble the DNA double helix. But we worried that this did not reflect the fracturing and trauma inherent in the poem. The next iteration was for an angular, Vorticist object with braille running along the faces on both sides. In this version I tried to represent a sense of anxiety while at the same time facilitating easy access to the braille. The final version came about from a thought to make each line from the poem an individual module and to connect them in a line with a popcorn joint embedded in the left side of each piece. We were concerned that the prior two versions, while impressive in size as 3D printed objects, would not be easily realizable on the average desktop 3D printer. In response to this I decided to break the poem up into smaller sections none of which any taller than 140mm, which most desktop machines can accommodate comfortably. “Future Biometrics” is written in six couplets with one single line at the end. I designed each set of two modules with different extrusion profiles so that the couplets could hopefully be discerned purely by touch. On the right side of each module is also a braille number to indicate the order in which the pieces should be connected.

The "Future Biometrics" modules are oriented in the correct direction for printing on an FFF machine. I recommend printing each module at 0.2mm layer height, 3 shells and 10-15% infill. They should print fine without rafts or support material. I have also included a zip file with the original braille STL files that Sean Tikkun generated. To produce your own 3D printable braille dots, download OpenSCAD here (http://openscad.org) and get Sean’s OpenSCAD braille generator (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:74358). If you are interested the Rhino 3D file used to create this piece can be accessed here: https://www.dropbox.com/s/0pzwch54wojy8t8/future-biometrics.3dm?dl=0

description.text:
I created this thing to mount my HK 2 axis Mobius gimbal to the Trifecta.  I designed it on SketchUp, and it's my first design ever, so it's very very crude.  Replace your Mobius or GoPro mount from HK and mount this instead.  The long platform can be ziptied, double side taped or screwed in to hold the original gimbal rubber mount.  Currently I'm still trying to get rid of the jello by replacing the rubber with zipties, no luck yet.  
Share it, use it, mod it, do whatever you want with it.  Just as long as you're not making a profit and that any mods you make, you share it with everyone too.  
Requires M2.5 x20mm or x25mm screw to secure it to the Trifecta frame.  I'm still looking for them, currently held on by bamboo skewers, which might be the reason I'm getting jello still.
